Election fraud at the Coast will not happen under the watchful eye of the opposition, two Coast governors said on Tuesday.Hassan Joho (Mombasa) and Amason Kingi (Kilifi) said they will implement the &lsquo;adopt-a-polling-station&rsquo; strategy as suggested by Cord leader Raila Odinga.The strategy will see the deployment of supports to guard votes at the country's 44,000 polling stations. Raila said it was used in Ghana&rsquo;s general election in December.&ldquo;Each polling station should have at least 58 people to guard our votes. We will employ the adopt-a-polling-station strategy to ensure our votes are protected,&rdquo; he said.Read:What Kenya Can Learn From Ghana&rsquo;s ElectionsThe opposition leader claimed on Tuesday that the NIS was interfering with voter registration by listing people in Uganda and Ethiopia. He alleged that the Jubilee government are planning to rig the August 8 polls using the Service.Read: [VIDEO] Raila links NIS to election fraud, voter listing in Uganda and EthiopiaJoho, who is ODM deputy leader, said he had credible information on officials of the NIS, police and the military who have been campaigning for Jubilee.&ldquo;We are warning them that after the election, we shall come for you and the law with take its course. We cannot allow government officers, paid using our taxes, to engage in politics,&rdquo; he said.&ldquo;As we speak, we have already received applications from people ready to sponsor the adoption of polling stations. We urge other regions to do the same, as it does not cost much to cater for the expenses of the people who will guard our votes."Read: How 2013 elections were rigged in favour of Uhuru, claims RailaKingi told the Jubilee government that, &ldquo;2013 was your last successful attempt in rigging the elections. This year it will not happen.&rdquo;Raila has vied for the presidency and lost in 1997, 2007 and 2013. He has complained of rigging in the past but has said he will not do so again.Kingi said the adopt-a-polling-station is their best option at ending the Jubilee government's rule.&ldquo;It better to be ruled by clueless leaders, as they call us in Cord, than to be ruled by Jubilee whose only agenda is theft,&rdquo; said Kingi.Among leaders who have echoed the sentiments by Raila, Kingi and Joho are MPs Omar Mwinyi (Changamwe), Rashid Bedzimba (Kisauni), Willy Mtengo (Malindi) and William Kamoti (Rabai.)Others are woman representatives Mishi Mboko (Mombasa) and Aisha Jumwa (Kilifi) and Kilifi Senator Stewart Madzayo.